definition.value: A fatty acid with a chain length ranging from C13 to C22.
A macrolide antibiotic that is tylonolide having mono- and diglycosyl moieties attached to two of its hydroxy groups..
The L-enantiomer of threonic acid.
The 5-phospho derivative of 2-dehydro-D-gluconic acid.
A pyridinemonocarboxylic acid that is pyridine in which the hydrogen at position 3 is replaced by a carboxy group.
A homopolymer macromolecule consisting of repeating glycerol-1-phosphate units.
A galactonolactone that is the D-enantiomer of galactono-1,5-lactone.
The open chain form of D-fructose 6-phosphate.
An acyclic carotene commonly obtained from tomatoes and other red fruits.

An organic heterobicyclic compound that consists of 2-oxohexahydro-1H-thieno[3,4-d]imidazole having a valeric acid substituent attached to the tetrahydrothiophene ring. The parent of the class of biotins.
A ribitol compound having meso-configuration. It occurs naturally in the plant Adonis vernalis.
An optically active form of glutamic acid having D-configuration.
The L-enantiomer of the amino acid histidine.
An sn-glycerol 3-phosphate having unsubstituted hydroxy groups.
A cobalamin in which the central cobalt atom has an oxidation state of +1.
A nucleobase-containing molecular entity with a polymeric structure comprised of a linear sequence of 13 or more nucleotide residues.
An N-acyl-D-glucosamine phosphate having the phosphate group placed at the 6-position.
A member of the class of  ethanolamines that is ethane with an amino substituent at C-1 and a hydroxy substituent at C-2, making it both a primary amine and a primary alcohol.
The D-enantiomer of glucaric acid.
An optically active form of lactate having (R)-configuration.
A hydroxybenzaldehyde carrying a hydroxy substituent at position 2.
An oxoproline having the oxo group placed at the 5-position. It is an intermediate metabolite in the glutathione cycle.
An optically active form of glutamic acid having L-configuration.
A ketotriose consisting of acetone bearing hydroxy substituents at positions 1 and 3. The simplest member of the class of ketoses and the parent of the class of glycerones.
A mannose with D-configuration.
A 2,6-diaminopimelic acid in which both chiral centres have S configuration. It is a component of bacterial cell wall.
A purine ribonucleoside 5'-monophosphate having adenine as the nucleobase.
A class of glycerophospholipids in which a phosphatidyl group is esterified to the hydroxy group of ethanolamine.
An aminopyrimidine that is pyrimidin-2-one having the amino group located at position 4.
A monoatomic monoanion resulting from the addition of an electron to any halogen atom.
The reduced 1,5-dihydro form of flavin mononucleotide.
An alkene that is propane with a double bond at position 1.
The acyclic form of L-rhamnose.

The 2-(3,4-dihydroxybenzoyl) derivative of 2,4,6-trihydroxybenzoic acid. A metabolite of quercetin, an abundant flavonoid found in edible vegetables, grains and fruits which is used as an ingredient in supplements, beverages, or foods.
A D-glucose monophosphate in which the phosphate group is located at position 1.
The (S)-enantiomer of 3-(indol-3-yl)-2-oxobutyric acid.
A D-fructofuranose 6-phosphate with a beta-configuration at the anomeric position.
Propan-1-ol with a hydrogen at each of the 3 carbon positions substituted with a carboxylate group.
A divalent inorganic anion obtained by removal of both protons from thiosulfuric acid.

The simplest member of the class of propane-1,3-diols, consisting of propane in which one hydrogen from each methyl group is substituted by a hydroxy group. A colourless, viscous, water-miscible liquid with a high (210degreeC) boiling point, it is used in the synthesis of certain polymers and as a solvent and antifreeze.
A cholestanoid consisting of cholestane having a double bond at the 5,6-position as well as a 3beta-hydroxy group.
An aminobenzoic acid that is anthranilic acid substituted by a hydroxy group at position 3 and a methyl group at position 4.
A 5-oxo monocarboxylic acid anion that is the conjugate base of 5-oxopentanoic acid, arising from deprotonation of the carboxy group.
The simplest member of the class of  cyclopentanols bearing a single hydroxy substituent. The parent of the class of cyclopentanols.
An azane that consists of a single nitrogen atom covelently bonded to three hydrogen atoms.
A branched fatty acid comprising propanoic acid carrying a methyl branch at C-2.
